  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - ENCHANTER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>STARTING AT 16, DERVS IN THE NRO....</font> - <small>Darkius Maximus, Erollisi Marr</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Starting at 16, an enchanter can keep a dervish camp clear in the North Ro Desert (NRO) all by his(her)self. Generally, this is derv1 (the derv camp nearest to the water and also the one that contains Dorn B'Dynn). Note that derv2 is far too large for a solo enchanter and, for some weird reasons, our animations wander off at derv3 (yes, i found this out the hard way).<p><p>
Normally, fighting takes place on the hill to the north of the camp so one is looking into the camp facing south. There are four spawn points: 3 for dervs and 1 for dorn. Keep darkelf illusion up at all times (to keep Dorn from agroing) though you will want to con him and make sure that everything is ok. As a human enchanter with darkelf illusion, Dorn conned indifferent so I was ok hanging around him. Make sure that you are fully buffed and so is your pet. At this point, my spells memorized were: Languid Pace, Ebbing Strength, Choke, Sanity Warp, Root, Mesmerize, Tashan and Gate.<p><p> 
From my own personal experience at derv1, here is the ranking of dervs from most powerful to weakest: Thug (looks like an ogre), Erudite Derv (looks like an erudite and is a nasty caster), Orc Derv (looks like an orc), Barbarian Derv (looks like a tall barbarian in leather armor), Human Monk Girl Derv (looks like a human female monk) and Female Ogre Derv (looks like a naked female ogre and is a weak caster). All the dervs except the casters will rush you as they are melee-based. The 2 casters will stand there and nuke you. Tactics for casters will be discussed below.<p><p>
Pulling is easy for melee-ers and tougher for spellcasters. Since casters stand in the spawn point (never a good idea to fight in a spawn zone), they are hard to draw out. I have noticed that, when fighting casters, if your hit points are low, make sure that you have Rune1 on and then nuke like crazy. Don't bother debuffing as you need to kill that caster as soon as possible. That strategy (if it can be called that) is mainly for the Erudite derv. The Female Ogre Derv is far easier and should fall rather quickly. She has much weaker offensive spells as well.<p><p>
Always take the so-called "outside" derv first. This is the derv who stands to the far left (remember we are facing south), nearest to the water and next to the flagpole. Move down to the flat area near the water and pull that derv to the beach. I usually pull with Languid Pace (it seems to have a greater range than Tashan) and, as it runs to me, I usually get off a Tashan as well. Let yourself get hit and then have your pet engage. Debuff that derv (Ebbing Strength) and root and nuke. Hopefully, you should have saved up enough cash for a dragoon dirk by now, so jump in there and melee with it if your pet gets low on life. Note that if the derv is a caster, follow the advice given above. Note that the "outside" derv is far enough away from the others, that you can pull that derv solo without bringing his/her friends as well! Of course, MAKE SURE that you pull to the beach (away from the camp) and you target the right derv.<p><p> 
Now that the flagpole derv is gone, there are 2 spawn spots remaining. I usually take the rightmost one next. Now, it is actually possible to pull that derv without annoying the center one...though it often takes a bit of experimentation to get it. At 16, you have to be real lucky to be able to take on 2 so perhaps some old fashioned enchanter crowd control is called for. Return to the hill on the north side of the derv camp, med and heal back to full from your last fight (hopefully, your pet BARELY survived). When ready, use soothe on the center derv (usually i replace root with soothe temporarily) and then pull the rightmost derv with languid pace. Do what you did on the previous fight and you should be ok.<p><p>
Now, dervs take some time to respawn so you should have 2 spawn points clear, 1 derv left and Dorn sitting peacefully in the camp. Take on the last one by pulling it up the hill. If you prefer to pull out of the camp (instead of through it), it is possible to move to the southside of the camp and pull out of the camp.<p><p>
After that fight, congratulations! You have kept a derv camp clear all by yourself! You are now the envy of your friends at your level! =) Med, heal and buff up until the flagpole derv spawns again. 
Some notes that maybe helpful to be aware of:<p><p> 
1) Rarely is derv1 uncamped by hordes of people but keep trying. If there is only one or two other people there around your level, they should be grateful for your presence - I don't think there is another class at 16 which can keep a derv camp clear solo. <p><p>
2) Killing Thugs is tough. These guys are top-notch melee-ers and boy do they hurt. I recommend rune1 for both you and your pet and keep a CLOSE EYE on your pet's health. If it starts getting low, jump in there and soak up some damage for it. I recommend that you practice on other dervs first before taking a derv thug solo.<p><p> 
3) Killing the Erudite Dervs is tough too. These guys know how to nuke. Hit them with tashan and then cut loose and burn mana. When the Erudite Derv nukes you, your pet should run over to him and start fighting. Note that fighting in a spawn point is inherently dangerous. Keep nuking to pull that derv out of there. Also, note that Dorn may agro on your pet if your pet is fighting in the camp. So, try to pull the Erudite Derv out of there as soon as possible. If you nuke it enough, it WILL come to you and start meleeing. If Dorn frenzies on your pet, gate out or run NOW! <p><p>
4) Keep the darkelf illusion up at all times. I've been saved by it MANY times. Usually when some careless paladin or elf comes to close to dorn and agros him. Dorn usually wipes out all the campers except for those of the evil races. Of course, the illusion isn't a guaranteed solution - I suggest vacating the area whenever Dorn gets annoyed.<p><p> 
5) Dervs are cowards - they turn into runners when they get low on hit points. Keep root around or be ready to nuke at the very end. You DO NOT want that wounded derv to make it back to a full camp of dervs. <p><p>
6) You should be making some nice cash if you can keep the derv camp clear all by yourself. That means you get all of the bronze weapons! Good show! You are buying the ale next time I see ya in Freeport! =) <p><p>
7) It happens sometimes. A spell doesn't take or a mistake is made or something and you find yourself fighting 2 or 3 dervs at once. DON'T PANIC. Not yet at any rate. Had this happen to me many times and here's my answer: If fighting all 3 dervs at once, mez as many as you need to (let the rest fight your pet) and gate out. Unless you are uber-enchanter, time to leave the area. If fighting 2, it is possible to actually get the kill for one before leaving. Mez the one that your pet is NOT fighting and debuff the other one. Drop choke and so forth so that your pet wins the fight but that you still have some mana left over to keep the other one mezzed. Now, if the pet dies, time to mez them both then gate or run. If the pet kills one and starts fighting the other one, loot the derv corpse and get out of there...your pet WON'T survive the second derv. This is all pretty risky of course...but then, you should be used to it by now - yer an enchanter. =)

</td></tr>
